write a record to the database. =C2=A0Each instance will have its own uuid =
which will be stored in the record in the database and then stored in an in=
stance variable for use by the AfterClass method. =C2=A0The AfterClass meth=
od will update that same record referred to by the uuid. =C2=A0If the Befor=
eClass is static I have to store the uuid in a static variable - which woul=
d result in the uuid being overwritten if multiple instances ran simultaneo=
usly. =C2=A0AfterClass could update the wrong record because the uuid had c=
hanged. =C2=A0I definitely don&#39;t want a static method if there is a chance =
the TestSuite could be executed simultaneously.
Making these methods static=
 is poor design. =C2=A0If you need static functionality in Before / After c=
lass methods, make those methods non-static and they can call a static meth=
od for the static functionality. =C2=A0Forcing them to be static creates co=
ncurrency issues if more than one instance runs concurrently.
If this still=
 doesn&#39;t make any sense to you look up concurrency issues with static metho=
ds.
